closed the doors. I... I... I...

939
00:53:42,833 --> 00:53:44,473
The whole town's gone crazy.

940
00:53:44,513 --> 00:53:45,953
Yes, h-hello?

941
00:53:45,993 --> 00:53:48,153
George, it's Potter.

942
00:53:51,953 --> 00:53:53,433
- Hello?
- George,

943
00:53:53,513 --> 00:53:58,993
there is a rumor around town that
you've closed your doors. Is that true?

944
00:53:59,033 --> 00:54:03,113
Oh, well, I'm very glad to hear
that. George, are you all right?

945
00:54:03,153 --> 00:54:06,833
- Do you need any police?
- Police? What's for?

946
00:54:06,873 --> 00:54:11,073
Well, mobs get pretty
ugly sometimes, you know.

947
00:54:11,153 --> 00:54:15,273
George, I'm going all out
to help in this crisis.

948
00:54:15,313 --> 00:54:20,753
I've just guaranteed the bank
sufficient funds to meet their needs.

949
00:54:20,793 --> 00:54:24,073
They'll close up for
a week and then reopen.

950
00:54:24,873 --> 00:54:26,153
He just took over the bank.

951
00:54:26,993 --> 00:54:32,513
I may lose a fortune, but I'm
willing to guarantee your people too.

952
00:54:32,593 --> 00:54:37,753
Just tell them to bring their shares over
here, and I will pay fifty cents on the dollar.

953
00:54:37,793 --> 00:54:39,993
Aw, you never miss a
trick, do you, Potter?

954
00:54:40,073 --> 00:54:41,073
Well, you're gonna miss this one.

955
00:54:41,113 --> 00:54:45,073
If you close your doors before
six P.M., you will never reopen.

956
00:54:53,793 --> 00:54:56,953
George, was it a nice wedding?
Gosh, I wanted to be there.

957
00:54:57,833 --> 00:54:58,953
Yeah...

958
00:55:00,793 --> 00:55:02,793
You can take this one off now.

959
00:55:11,513 --> 00:55:16,953
Now, just remember that this
thing isn't as black as it appears.

960
00:55:26,513 --> 00:55:28,273
I have some news for you folks.

961
00:55:28,313 --> 00:55:31,593
I was just talking to old man Potter and
he's guaranteed cash payments at the bank.

962
00:55:31,633 --> 00:55:33,393
The bank's going to reopen next week.

963
00:55:33,433 --> 00:55:35,113
But, George, I got my money here.

964
00:55:35,193 --> 00:55:36,873
Did he guarantee this place?

965
00:55:36,913 --> 00:55:38,673
Well, no, Charlie. I
didn't even ask him.

966
00:55:38,713 --> 00:55:41,393
- We don't need Potter over here.
- I'll take mine now.

967
00:55:42,073 --> 00:55:46,593
No, but you... you... you're
thinking of this place all wrong.

968
00:55:46,633 --> 00:55:48,433
As if I had the money back in a safe.

969
00:55:48,473 --> 00:55:50,473
The, the money's not here.

970
00:55:50,513 --> 00:55:52,993
Well, your money's in Joe's
house... that's right next to yours.

971
00:55:53,033 --> 00:55:56,993
And in the Kennedy House, and Mrs.
Macklin's house, and, and a hundred others.

972
00:55:57,033 --> 00:55:58,793
Why, you're lending
them the money to build,

973
00:55:58,833 --> 00:56:00,553
and then, they're going to pay
it back to you as best they can.

974
00:56:00,633 --> 00:56:02,913
Now what are you going
to do? Foreclose on them?

975
00:56:02,953 --> 00:56:05,153
I got two hundred and
forty-two dollars in here

976
00:56:05,193 --> 00:56:08,673
and two hundred and forty-two
dollars isn't going to break anybody.

977
00:56:09,553 --> 00:56:12,793
Okay, Tom. All right. Here
you are. You sign this.

978
00:56:12,833 --> 00:56:15,993
- You'll get your money in sixty days.
- Sixty days?

979
00:56:16,073 --> 00:56:18,233
Well, now that's what you agreed
to when you bought you shares.

980
00:56:18,273 --> 00:56:20,313
- Tom... Tom... Did you get your money?
- No.

981
00:56:20,353 --> 00:56:24,153
Well, I did. Old man Potter'll pay fifty
cents on the dollar for every share you got.

982
00:56:24,193 --> 00:56:26,913
- Fifty cents on the dollar!
- Yes, cash!

983
00:56:26,953 --> 00:56:29,513
- Well, what do you say?
- Now, Tom,

984
00:56:29,593 --> 00:56:31,233
you have to stick to
your original agreement.

985
00:56:31,273 --> 00:56:33,753
- Now give us sixty days on this.
- Okay, Randall.

986
00:56:33,793 --> 00:56:36,633
- Are you going to go to Potter's?
- Better get half than nothing.

987
00:56:37,033 --> 00:56:39,593
Tom! Tom!

988
00:56:39,633 --> 00:56:41,673
Randall, now wait a minute, wait...

989
00:56:41,713 --> 00:56:43,633
now listen... now listen to me.

990
00:56:43,713 --> 00:56:46,033
I-I beg of you not to do this thing.

991
00:56:46,073 --> 00:56:47,753
If Potter gets ahold of
this Building and Loan,

992
00:56:47,793 --> 00:56:50,073
there'll never be another
decent house built in this town.

993
00:56:50,153 --> 00:56:52,353
He's already got charge of the
bank. He's got the bus line.

994
00:56:52,433 --> 00:56:54,673
He's got the department
stores. And now he's after us.

995
00:56:54,713 --> 00:56:56,193
Why? Well, it's very simple.

996
00:56:56,233 --> 00:56:58,553
Because we're cutting in
on his business, that's why.

997
00:56:58,593 --> 00:57:00,833
And because he wants to
keep you living in his slums

998
00:57:00,873 --> 00:57:02,873
and paying the kind
of rent he decides.

999
00:57:02,913 --> 00:57:05,713
Joe, you had one of those Potter houses,
didn't you? Well, have you forgotten?

1000
00:57:05,753 --> 00:57:08,513
Have you forgotten what he
charged for that broken-down shack?

1001
00:57:08,553 --> 00:57:11,553
Here, Ed. You know, you remember last
year when things weren't going so well,

1002
00:57:11,593 --> 00:57:12,833
you couldn't make your payments.

1003
00:57:12,873 --> 00:57:15,953
You didn't lose your house, did you? Do
you think Potter would have let you keep it?

1004
00:57:16,033 --> 00:57:19,033
Ca-Can't you understand
what's happening here?

1005
00:57:19,073 --> 00:57:20,713
Don't you see what's happening?

1006
00:57:20,753 --> 00:57:22,873
Potter isn't selling. Potter's buying.

1007
00:57:22,913 --> 00:57:25,833
And why? Because we're panicky
and he's not. That's why.

1008
00:57:25,913 --> 00:57:26,953
He's picking up some bargains.

1009
00:57:26,993 --> 00:57:29,553
Now, We-We can get through
this thing all right.

1010
00:57:29,633 --> 00:57:32,993
We-We've got to stick together, though.
We've got to have faith in each other.

1011
00:57:33,033 --> 00:57:36,113
But my husband hasn't worked
in over a year and I need money.

1012
00:57:36,193 --> 00:57:39,553
- How am I going to live until the bank opens?
- I got doctor bills to pay.

1013
00:57:39,593 --> 00:57:42,193
- I need cash.
- I can't feed my kids on faith.

1014
00:57:42,233 --> 00:57:44,233
How much do you need?

1015
00:57:44,273 --> 00:57:47,593
Hey! I got two thousand dollars.

1016
00:57:48,473 --> 00:57:51,073
Here's two thousand dollars. This'll
tide us over until the bank reopens.

1017
00:57:51,113 --> 00:57:52,433
All right, Tom, how much do you need?

1018
00:57:52,473 --> 00:57:53,713
Two hundred and forty-two dollars.

1019
00:57:53,753 --> 00:57:56,193
Aw, Tom, just enough to tide
you over till the bank reopens.

1020
00:57:56,233 --> 00:57:58,913
I'll take two hundred
and forty-two dollars.

1021
00:58:01,313 --> 00:58:03,433
- There you are.
- That'll close my account.

1022
00:58:03,473 --> 00:58:05,553
Your account's still
here. That's a loan.

1023
00:58:05,633 --> 00:58:07,273
Okay. All right, Ed?

1024
00:58:07,313 --> 00:58:09,633
- I got three hundred dollars here, George.
- Alright, now, Ed...

1025
00:58:09,713 --> 00:58:12,633
wh-wh-what'll it take till the
bank opens? What do you need?

1026
00:58:12,673 --> 00:58:16,953
- Well, I-I suppose twenty dollars.
- Twenty dollars. Now you're talking.

1027
00:58:16,993 --> 00:58:18,073
Fine. Thanks, Ed.

1028
00:58:18,153 --> 00:58:19,713
All right now, Mrs. Thompson,
how much do you want?

1029
00:58:19,753 --> 00:58:21,593
- But it's your own money, George.
- Never mind about that.

1030
00:58:21,633 --> 00:58:24,073
- How much do you want?
- I can get along with twenty, all right.

1031
00:58:24,113 --> 00:58:26,073
- Twenty dollars.
- And I'll sign a paper.

1032
00:58:26,113 --> 00:58:27,153
You don't have to sign anything.

1033
00:58:27,193 --> 00:58:29,073
I know you-you'll
pay it when you can.

1034
00:58:29,113 --> 00:58:30,913
That's okay. All right, Mrs. Davis?

1035
00:58:30,953 --> 00:58:35,033
- Could I have
seventeen-fifty? - Seven...

1036
00:58:35,073 --> 00:58:38,113
Bless your heart, of course you
can have it. You got fifty cents?

1037
00:58:38,153 --> 00:58:39,513
- Seven...
- We're going to make it, George.

1038
00:58:39,553 --> 00:58:43,393
- They'll never close us up today!
- Six, five, four,

1039
00:58:43,433 --> 00:58:46,673
three, two, one...

1040
00:58:46,713 --> 00:58:47,993
Bingo!

1041
00:58:48,033 --> 00:58:50,193
We made it. Close the door,
Ernie. We made it. Look.

1042
00:58:50,233 --> 00:58:52,353
Look, we're still in business.
We're still got two bucks left.

1043
00:58:52,433 --> 00:58:54,513
Well, look, let's have some
of that. Let's celebrate, huh.

1044
00:58:54,553 --> 00:58:56,033
G-Get some glasses, Tilly.

1045
00:58:56,113 --> 00:58:57,953
Well, a couple of financial wizards.

1046
00:58:57,993 --> 00:58:59,553
Those Rockefellers.

1047
00:58:59,593 --> 00:59:01,993
Get a tray for these two great
big important simoleans here.

1048
00:59:02,073 --> 00:59:03,633
We'll save them for seed. A toast.

1049
00:59:03,673 --> 00:59:07,033
A toast! A toast to Mama
Dollar and to Papa Dollar,

1050
00:59:07,073 --> 00:59:09,393
and if you want to keep this old
Building and Loan in business,

1051
00:59:09,433 --> 00:59:11,673
- you better have a family real quick.
- I wish they were rabbits.

1052
00:59:11,753 --> 00:59:12,993
I wish they were, too.

1053
00:59:14,153 --> 00:59:16,513
Okay, let's put them in
safe and see what happens.

1054
00:59:25,793 --> 00:59:29,353
- Folks, folks, wedding
cigars! - Oh-oh... wedding!

1055
00:59:30,527 --> 00:59:34,007
Holy mackerel, I'm married!
Where's Mary? Mary...

1056
00:59:34,087 --> 00:59:35,047
Well, poor Mary.

1057
00:59:35,087 --> 00:59:37,167
Look, I've got a train to
catch. Well, the train's gone.

1058
00:59:37,247 --> 00:59:39,807
I wonder if Ernie's still
here with his taxicab?

1059
00:59:39,847 --> 00:59:42,207
George, there's a call for you.

1060
00:59:42,247 --> 00:59:45,087
Look, will you get my wife on the phone?
She's probably over at her mother's.

1061
00:59:45,127 --> 00:59:47,967
- Mrs. Bailey is on the phone.
- I don't want Mrs. Bailey.

1062
00:59:48,007 --> 00:59:50,807
I want my wife. Mrs. Bailey!
Mrs... oh, that's my wife.

1063
00:59:50,887 --> 00:59:52,807
Here, I'll take it in here.

1064
00:59:52,847 --> 00:59:56,367
Mary! Hello. Listen,
dear. I'm sorry...

1065
00:59:56,407 --> 01:00:00,767
What? Come home? What home?

1066
01:00:00,807 --> 01:00:02,967
Three-twenty Sycamore? Well, what...

1067
01:00:03,007 --> 01:00:08,007
whose home is that?
The Waldorf Hotel, huh?

1068
01:00:18,167 --> 01:00:20,967
Hey, this is the company's posters,
and the company won't like this.

1069
01:00:21,047 --> 01:00:23,127
How would you like to
get a ticket next week?

1070
01:00:23,167 --> 01:00:26,087
- Haven't you any romance in you?
- Sure I have, but I got rid of it.

1071
01:00:26,167 --> 01:00:27,207
Liver pills!

1072
01:00:27,247 --> 01:00:30,047
Who wants to see liver
pills on their honeymoon?

1073
01:00:30,087 --> 01:00:34,047
What we want is romantic places, beautiful
places... places George wants to go.

1074
01:00:35,527 --> 01:00:38,647
- Hey, Bert. Here he comes.
- Come on, we got to get this up. He's coming.

1075
01:00:38,687 --> 01:00:40,527
- Who?
- The groom, idiot.

1076
01:00:40,567 --> 01:00:42,527
This is their honeymoon.
Come on. Get that ladder.

1077
01:00:42,567 --> 01:00:43,847
What are they
- ducks?

1078
01:00:46,967 --> 01:00:49,367
- Get that ladder up here.
- All right, all right.

1079
01:00:49,407 --> 01:00:51,767
- Hurry up. Hurry up. Hurry up.
- I'm hurrying.

1080
01:01:01,207 --> 01:01:03,847
Hiya... Geo... uh...
good evening, sir.

1081
01:01:06,007 --> 01:01:07,847
Entree, Monsieur.

1082
01:01:09,407 --> 01:01:17,967
- Entree.
- Islands of Hawaii,

1083
01:01:18,047 --> 01:01:27,247
Where skies of blue are calling me.

1084
01:01:27,287 --> 01:01:36,487
Where balmy air and golden moonlight

1085
01:01:36,527 --> 01:01:45,687
caress The waving palms of Waikiki.

1086
01:02:29,207 --> 01:02:31,207
Welcome home, Mr. Bailey.

1087
01:02:36,607 --> 01:02:38,647
Well, I'll be...

1088
01:02:43,527 --> 01:02:45,927
Mary, where did you...

1089
01:02:52,447 --> 01:02:58,087
I Love You Truly,

1090
01:02:58,127 --> 01:03:03,167
Truly, Dear.

1091
01:03:03,207 --> 01:03:07,727
Life with Its Shadows,

1092
01:03:07,807 --> 01:03:08,767
Oh, Mary...

1093
01:03:08,847 --> 01:03:11,607
Life with Its Tears.

1094
01:03:11,647 --> 01:03:13,407
Remember the night we broke
the windows in this old house?

1095
01:03:13,447 --> 01:03:18,847
Fade into Dreams,
- This is what I wished for.

1096
01:03:18,887 --> 01:03:22,807
When I Feel You Are Near,

1097
01:03:22,847 --> 01:03:32,527
- Darling, you're
wonderful. I Love You Truly,

1098
01:03:32,607 --> 01:03:39,607
Truly, Dear.

1099
01:03:47,967 --> 01:03:52,167
- Martini, you rented a new house?
- Rent?

1100
01:03:53,407 --> 01:03:55,927
- You hear what he say, Mr. Bailey?
- What's that?

1101
01:03:55,967 --> 01:03:57,847
I own the house.

1102
01:03:57,887 --> 01:04:01,247
Me, Giuseppe Martini,
I own my own house.

1103
01:04:01,287 --> 01:04:04,727
No more we live like pigs
in this Potter's Field.

1104
01:04:04,767 --> 01:04:06,127
Hurry, Marie!

1105
01:04:06,167 --> 01:04:07,607
Come on... Bring the baby.

1106
01:04:08,447 --> 01:04:10,287
This is like a dream!

1107
01:04:10,327 --> 01:04:11,887
I'll take the kids in the car.

1108
01:04:11,967 --> 01:04:13,727
Oh, thank you, Mr. Bailey.

1109
01:04:13,767 --> 01:04:15,487
All right, kids. Here.

1110
01:04:15,527 --> 01:04:16,527
Get in here.

1111
01:04:16,567 --> 01:04:18,527
Now get right up on the seat there.

1112
01:04:20,767 --> 01:04:22,647
Get the... get the dog!

1113
01:04:24,687 --> 01:04:26,447
You've got a goat too!

1114
01:04:27,767 --> 01:04:33,447
- All right. Goodbye.
- Goodbye, everybody!

1115
01:04:36,127 --> 01:04:37,167
All in.

1116
01:04:55,887 --> 01:04:58,007
Mr. And Mrs. Martini, welcome home.

1117
01:04:58,807 --> 01:05:01,087
Good old George. He's
always making a speech.

1118
01:05:02,367 --> 01:05:04,127
Hee-haw!

1119
01:05:04,207 --> 01:05:08,127
- Sam Wainwright!
- Oh, who cares!

1120
01:05:08,207 --> 01:05:11,207
Bread! That this house
may never know hunger.

1121
01:05:12,007 --> 01:05:15,447
Salt! That life may
always have flavor!

1122
01:05:15,487 --> 01:05:19,287
And wine!! That joy and
prosperity may reign forever.

1123
01:05:19,327 --> 01:05:21,207
Enter the Martini castle!

1124
01:05:22,927 --> 01:05:25,327
Look, Mr. Potter, it's
no skin off my nose.

1125
01:05:25,407 --> 01:05:27,167
I'm just your little rent collector.

1126
01:05:27,207 --> 01:05:31,047
But you can't laugh off this
Bailey Park anymore. Look at it.

1127
01:05:32,327 --> 01:05:34,807
Congressman Black is here to see you.

1128
01:05:34,847 --> 01:05:37,207
Oh, tell the congressman
to wait. Go on.

1129
01:05:37,287 --> 01:05:39,887
Fifteen years ago, a half-dozen
houses stuck here and there.

1130
01:05:39,927 --> 01:05:42,487
There's the old cemetery,
squirrels, buttercups, daisies.

1131
01:05:42,527 --> 01:05:44,287
I used to hunt rabbits there myself.

1132
01:05:45,687 --> 01:05:47,047
Look at it today.

1133
01:05:47,087 --> 01:05:50,047
Dozens of the prettiest
little homes you ever saw.

1134
01:05:50,087 --> 01:05:53,447
Ninety per cent owned by suckers
who used to pay rent to you!

1135
01:05:53,527 --> 01:05:56,807
Your Potter's Field, my dear Mr.
Employer, is becoming just that.

1136
01:05:56,847 --> 01:06:00,367
And are the local yokels making with
those David and Goliath wisecracks.

1137
01:06:00,447 --> 01:06:02,047
Oh, they are, are they?

1138
01:06:02,087 --> 01:06:04,967
Even though they know the Baileys
never made a dime out of it.

1139
01:06:05,047 --> 01:06:06,207
You know very well why,

1140
01:06:06,287 --> 01:06:07,607
the Baileys were all chumps.

1141
01:06:07,687 --> 01:06:11,847
Every one of these homes is worth twice
what it cost the Building and Loan to build.

1142
01:06:11,887 --> 01:06:14,527
- If I were you, Mr. Potter...
- Well, you are not me.

1143
01:06:14,567 --> 01:06:17,887
As I say, it's no skin off my nose.

1144
01:06:21,167 --> 01:06:25,567
But one of these days this bright young man
is going to be asking George Bailey for a job.

1145
01:06:28,247 --> 01:06:31,807
The Bailey family has been a
boil on my neck long enough.

1146
01:06:31,887 --> 01:06:33,087
- Yes, sir?
- Come in here.

1147
01:06:33,807 --> 01:06:36,087
We just stopped in town to take a
look at the new factory, and then

1148
01:06:36,127 --> 01:06:38,047
- we're going to drive on down to Florida.
- Oh...

1149
01:06:38,127 --> 01:06:40,647
- Why don't you have your friends join us?
- Why, sure.

1150
01:06:40,687 --> 01:06:43,567
Hey, why don't you kids
drive down with us, huh?

1151
01:06:43,607 --> 01:06:46,367
Oh, I'm afraid I
couldn't get away, Sam.

1152
01:06:46,407 --> 01:06:48,447
Still got the nose to
the old grindstone, eh?

1153
01:06:48,487 --> 01:06:53,447
Jane, I offered to let George in on the ground
floor in plastics and he turned me down cold.

1154
01:06:53,487 --> 01:06:56,207
- Oh, now don't rub it in.
- I'm not rubbing it in.

1155
01:06:56,247 --> 01:06:57,967
Well, I guess we better run along.

1156
01:06:58,007 --> 01:06:59,327
Awfully glad to have met you, Mary.

1157
01:06:59,367 --> 01:07:00,607
- Nice meeting you.
- Goodbye.

1158
01:07:00,647 --> 01:07:02,047
- Goodbye, George.
- So long, George.

1159
01:07:02,087 --> 01:07:03,767
- See you in the funny papers.
- Goodbye, Sam.

1160
01:07:03,807 --> 01:07:05,447
- So long, Mary.
- So long, Sam. Have fun.

1161
01:07:05,487 --> 01:07:06,527
Thanks for dropping around.

1162
01:07:06,567 --> 01:07:08,327
Florida! Hee-haw!

1163
01:07:08,367 --> 01:07:09,407
Hee-haw.

1164
01:07:38,647 --> 01:07:39,727
Thank you, sir.

1165
01:07:40,327 --> 01:07:41,607
Quite a cigar, Mr. Potter.

1166
01:07:41,647 --> 01:07:44,127
You like it? I'll send you a box.

1167
01:07:52,807 --> 01:07:56,087
Well, I, uh, I suppose I'll
find out sooner or later,

1168
01:07:56,127 --> 01:07:59,367
but just what exactly did
you want to see me about?

1169
01:08:01,087 --> 01:08:06,287
George, now that's just what
I like so much about you.

1170
01:08:06,327 --> 01:08:10,007
George, I'm an old man,
and most people hate me.

1171
01:08:10,047 --> 01:08:13,007
But I don't like them, either,
so that that makes it all even.

1172
01:08:13,047 --> 01:08:18,087
You know, just as well as I do, that I
run practically everything in this town

1173
01:08:18,127 --> 01:08:20,967
but the Bailey Building and Loan.

1174
01:08:21,007 --> 01:08:25,727
You know, also, that for a number of years I've
been trying to get control of it or kill it.

1175
01:08:25,807 --> 01:08:28,087
But I haven't been able to do it.

1176
01:08:28,127 --> 01:08:31,007
You have been stopping me.

1177
01:08:31,087 --> 01:08:34,327
In fact, you have beaten me, George,

1178
01:08:34,407 --> 01:08:39,447
and as anyone in this county can
tell you, that takes some doing.

1179
01:08:39,527 --> 01:08:42,647
Take during the
depression, for instance.

1180
01:08:42,687 --> 01:08:45,927
You and I were the only
ones that kept our heads.

1181
01:08:45,967 --> 01:08:49,287
You saved the Building and
Loan, I saved all the rest.

1182
01:08:49,367 --> 01:08:53,127
Yeah. Well, most people
say you stole all the rest.

1183
01:08:53,167 --> 01:08:56,927
The envious ones say
that, George, the suckers.

1184
01:08:56,967 --> 01:09:01,447
Now, I have stated
my side very frankly.

1185
01:09:01,527 --> 01:09:04,407
Now, let's look at your side.

1186
01:09:04,447 --> 01:09:11,407
Young man, twenty-seven, twenty-eight,
married, making say... forty a week.

1187
01:09:11,447 --> 01:09:14,407
- Forty-five! -
Forty-five. Forty-five.

1188
01:09:14,487 --> 01:09:17,367
Out of which, after
supporting your mother

1189
01:09:17,407 --> 01:09:22,007
and paying your bills, you're able
to keep, say ten, if you skimp.

1190
01:09:34,558 --> 01:09:38,678
But, George Bailey is not
a common, ordinary yokel.

1191
01:09:38,758 --> 01:09:42,798
He's an intelligent,
smart, ambitious young man,

1192
01:09:42,838 --> 01:09:48,038
who hates his job, who hates the
Building and Loan, almost as much as I do.

1193
01:09:48,078 --> 01:09:53,238
A young man who's been dying to get
out on his own ever since he was born.

1194
01:09:53,278 --> 01:09:56,238
A young man... the smartest
one of the crowd, mind you,

1195
01:09:56,278 --> 01:09:59,718
a young man who has to sit by
and watch his friends go places,

1196
01:09:59,758 --> 01:10:01,358
because he's trapped.

1197
01:10:01,438 --> 01:10:09,318
Yes, sir, trapped into frittering his life away
playing nursemaid to a lot of garlic-eaters.

1198
01:10:09,398 --> 01:10:12,718
Do I paint a correct
picture, or do I exaggerate?

1199
01:10:14,958 --> 01:10:16,438
Oh, what's your point, Mr. Potter?

1200
01:10:16,518 --> 01:10:20,158
- My point? My point is, I want to hire you.
- Hire me?

1201
01:10:20,198 --> 01:10:23,758
I want you to manage my
affairs, run my properties.

1202
01:10:23,798 --> 01:10:28,918
George, I'll start you out at
twenty thousand dollars a year.

1203
01:10:32,838 --> 01:10:35,838
Twenty thous... twenty
thousand dollars a year?

1204
01:10:35,878 --> 01:10:39,318
You wouldn't mind living
in the nicest house in town,

1205
01:10:39,398 --> 01:10:41,918
buying your wife a
lot of fine clothes,

1206
01:10:41,958 --> 01:10:46,798
a couple of business trips to New York
a year, maybe once in a while Europe.

1207
01:10:46,838 --> 01:10:48,438
You wouldn't mind
that, would you, George?

1208
01:10:48,518 --> 01:10:49,878
Would I?

1209
01:10:52,678 --> 01:10:55,118
Y-You're not talking to somebody
else around here, are you?

1210
01:10:55,158 --> 01:10:59,158
You know, th-this is me, you
remember me? George Bailey.

1211
01:10:59,198 --> 01:11:03,118
Oh, yes, George Bailey.
Whose ship has just come in,

1212
01:11:03,158 --> 01:11:06,478
provided he has enough
brains to climb aboard.

1213
01:11:14,838 --> 01:11:16,118
Holy mackerel!

1214
01:11:19,158 --> 01:11:21,678
Well, how about the Building and Loan?

1215
01:11:21,718 --> 01:11:25,318
Oh, confound it, man!
Are you afraid of success?

1216
01:11:25,358 --> 01:11:30,398
I'm offering you a three-year contract at
twenty thousand dollars a year, starting today.

1217
01:11:30,438 --> 01:11:32,238
Is it a deal, or isn't it?

1218
01:11:33,878 --> 01:11:35,598
Well, Mr. Potter, I...

1219
01:11:35,638 --> 01:11:40,438
I... I know I ought to jump at
the chance but I... I just, uh,

1220
01:11:40,478 --> 01:11:44,438
I-I wonder if-if it would be possible for you
to give me twenty-four hours to think it over?

1221
01:11:44,478 --> 01:11:46,238
Sure, sure, sure.

1222
01:11:46,278 --> 01:11:49,038
You go on home and talk
about it to your wife.

1223
01:11:49,078 --> 01:11:50,598
- I'd like to do that.
- Yeah.

1224
01:11:50,638 --> 01:11:52,958
In the meantime, I'll
draw up the papers.

1225
01:11:52,998 --> 01:11:55,238
- All right, sir.
- Okay, George?

1226
01:11:56,598 --> 01:11:58,118
Okay, Mr. Potter.

1227
01:12:08,398 --> 01:12:11,278
No, no, no, no. Wait a
minute here. Wait a minute.

1228
01:12:11,318 --> 01:12:14,398
I don't need twenty-four hours.
I, I don't have to talk to anybody.

1229
01:12:14,438 --> 01:12:16,558
I know right now, and
the answer is no! No!

1230
01:12:16,598 --> 01:12:18,078
Doggone it!

1231
01:12:18,118 --> 01:12:20,678
You sit around here and
you spin your little webs

1232
01:12:20,718 --> 01:12:22,918
and you think the whole world
revolves around you and your money.

1233
01:12:22,958 --> 01:12:24,718
Well, it doesn't, Mr. Potter.

1234
01:12:24,798 --> 01:12:27,878
In the... in the whole vast
configuration of things,

1235
01:12:27,918 --> 01:12:30,958
I'd say you were nothing
but a scurvy little spider.

1236
01:12:30,998 --> 01:12:35,718
You... and that goes for you, too.

1237
01:12:39,638 --> 01:12:41,998
And it goes for you, too.

1238
01:12:48,718 --> 01:12:52,238
If you wouldn't mind living
in the nicest house in town.

1239
01:12:52,278 --> 01:12:55,078
Buying your wife a
lot of fine clothes.

1240
01:12:55,118 --> 01:12:58,638
Going to New York on a business
trip a couple of times a year.

1241
01:12:58,678 --> 01:13:01,198
Maybe to Europe once in a while.

1242
01:13:01,918 --> 01:13:03,758
I know what I'm going to do tomorrow

1243
01:13:03,798 --> 01:13:07,078
and the next day and next
year and the hear after that.

1244
01:13:07,158 --> 01:13:12,318
I'm shaking the dust of this crummy little
town off my feet, and I'm going to see the world

1245
01:13:12,398 --> 01:13:15,198
and then I'm going to build things.
I'm going to build air fields.

1246
01:13:15,238 --> 01:13:18,118
I'm going to build skyscrapers
a hundred stories high.

1247
01:13:18,198 --> 01:13:21,598
I'm going to build
a bridge a mile long.

1248
01:13:21,638 --> 01:13:23,318
What is it you want,

1249
01:13:23,358 --> 01:13:25,198
Mary? What? Y-You want the moon?

1250
01:13:25,238 --> 01:13:27,798
If you do, just say the word,
I'll throw a lasso around it

1251
01:13:27,838 --> 01:13:29,838
and pulls her down for you.

1252
01:13:29,878 --> 01:13:32,318
Buffalo Gals, won't
you come out tonight,

1253
01:13:32,358 --> 01:13:35,358
Won't you come out tonight,
Won't you come out tonight.

1254
01:13:35,398 --> 01:13:38,758
Buffalo Gals, won't
you come out tonight,

1255
01:13:38,798 --> 01:13:40,798
And...

1256
01:13:46,918 --> 01:13:48,558
- Hi.
- Hi.

1257
01:13:54,078 --> 01:13:55,478
Mary Hatch!

1258
01:13:57,838 --> 01:14:02,038
Wh-Why in the world did you
ever marry a guy like me?

1259
01:14:02,118 --> 01:14:04,558
To keep from being an old maid.

1260
01:14:04,598 --> 01:14:08,678
You could have married Sam
Wainwright and anybody else in town.

1261
01:14:08,718 --> 01:14:12,078
I didn't want to marry
anybody else in town.

1262
01:14:12,158 --> 01:14:14,278
I want my baby to look like you.

1263
01:14:14,358 --> 01:14:17,198
You didn't even have a honeymoon.

1264
01:14:17,238 --> 01:14:20,038
I promised you... your what?

1265
01:14:20,078 --> 01:14:22,598
My baby.

1266
01:14:22,638 --> 01:14:27,958
You... You-You-You-You-You-You-You...
Mary, you're on the nest?

1267
01:14:27,998 --> 01:14:30,638
George Bailey lassoes stork.

1268
01:14:30,718 --> 01:14:32,118
Lassoes the stork!

1269
01:14:34,118 --> 01:14:35,878
What do you...

1270
01:14:35,918 --> 01:14:37,878
You mean...
you-you-you...

1271
01:14:37,918 --> 01:14:40,158
What-what-what is
it, a boy or a girl?

1272
01:14:40,198 --> 01:14:41,398
Uh-hm.

1273
01:14:43,478 --> 01:14:48,038
Now, you've probably already guessed
that George never leaves Bedford Falls.

1274
01:14:48,118 --> 01:14:49,038
No!

1275
01:14:49,078 --> 01:14:52,158
Mary had her baby, a boy.

1276
01:14:52,198 --> 01:14:54,638
Then she had another one, a girl.

1277
01:14:54,678 --> 01:14:59,958
Day after day she worked away remaking
the old Granville house into a home.

1278
01:14:59,998 --> 01:15:03,638
Night after night, George
came back late from the office.

1279
01:15:07,238 --> 01:15:09,478
Potter was bearing down hard.

1280
01:15:14,678 --> 01:15:16,438
Then came a war.

1281
01:15:17,078 --> 01:15:21,118
Ma Bailey and Mrs. Hatch
joined the Red Cross and sewed.

1282
01:15:21,158 --> 01:15:25,398
Mary had two more babies but
still found time to run the U.S.O.

1283
01:15:25,438 --> 01:15:29,398
Sam Wainwright made a fortune
in plastic hoods for planes.

1284
01:15:29,438 --> 01:15:32,198
Potter became head of the draft board.

1285
01:15:32,238 --> 01:15:40,278
One-A...
one-A... one-A

1286
01:15:40,318 --> 01:15:43,078
Gower and Uncle Billy sold war bonds.

1287
01:15:43,118 --> 01:15:47,718
Bert the cop was wounded in
North Africa, got the Silver Star.

1288
01:15:47,758 --> 01:15:51,558
Ernie, the taxi-driver,
parachuted into France.

1289
01:15:51,598 --> 01:15:55,158
Marty helped capture
the Remagen Bridge.

1290
01:15:55,238 --> 01:15:58,678
Harry, Harry Bailey topped them all.

1291
01:15:58,758 --> 01:16:02,478
A Navy flier, he shot
down fifteen planes.

1292
01:16:02,518 --> 01:16:06,878
Two of them as they were about to
crash into a transport full of soldiers.

1293
01:16:08,318 --> 01:16:10,998
- Yes, but George...
- George?

1294
01:16:11,038 --> 01:16:16,198
Four-F on account of his ear, George
fought the battle of Bedford Falls.

1295
01:16:16,238 --> 01:16:18,118
Hold on, hold on, hold on now.

1296
01:16:18,158 --> 01:16:19,998
Don't you know there's a war on?

1297
01:16:20,038 --> 01:16:22,198
Air raid warden...

1298
01:16:30,678 --> 01:16:35,718
paper drives... scrap
drives... rubber drives...

1299
01:16:35,758 --> 01:16:40,758
Like everybody else, on
V-E day he wept and prayed.

1300
01:16:40,798 --> 01:16:44,398
On V-J day, he wept and prayed again.

1301
01:16:44,478 --> 01:16:48,038
Joseph, now show him
what happened today.

1302
01:16:48,078 --> 01:16:49,318
Yes, sir.

1303
01:16:49,358 --> 01:16:54,238
This morning, day before Christmas,
about ten A.M., Bedford Falls Time.

1304
01:16:54,318 --> 01:16:56,798
Hi, Ernie, look at that.

1305
01:17:02,078 --> 01:17:03,118
Gonna snow again.

1306
01:17:03,158 --> 01:17:06,478
What do you mean it's gonna
snow? Look at the headlines.

1307
01:17:06,518 --> 01:17:08,958
I know, I know, George.
And it's marvelous.

1308
01:17:08,998 --> 01:17:10,718
Commander Harry Bailey!

1309
01:17:10,758 --> 01:17:12,358
Mr. Gower, look at this.

1310
01:17:12,438 --> 01:17:14,478
The second page. Now
look, this is for you.

1311
01:17:14,518 --> 01:17:16,278
This is for you. That's for you.

1312
01:17:16,318 --> 01:17:17,958
- Thanks.
- See you again.

1313
01:17:19,558 --> 01:17:21,718
Be sure you spell the name right.

1314
01:17:21,798 --> 01:17:23,638
Hello, Billy, how are you?

1315
01:17:31,798 --> 01:17:34,478
Extra! Extra! Read all about it!

1316
01:17:34,518 --> 01:17:36,798
George! George! It's Harry now
on long distance from Washington.

1317
01:17:36,878 --> 01:17:39,838
- Harry! What do you know about that!
- He reversed the charges. It's okay, isn't it?

1318
01:17:39,878 --> 01:17:42,478
Reverse the charges...
of course it's for a hero.

1319
01:17:42,558 --> 01:17:43,958
Harry...

1320
01:17:43,998 --> 01:17:46,958
Oh, you old seven
times of a son of a gun.

1321
01:17:47,038 --> 01:17:48,198
Congratulations!

1322
01:17:48,238 --> 01:17:49,958
How's mother standing it?

1323
01:17:50,038 --> 01:17:51,358
She did?

1324
01:17:51,398 --> 01:17:52,438
What do you know...

1325
01:17:52,518 --> 01:17:54,078
Mother had lunch with
the President's wife.

1326
01:17:54,118 --> 01:17:55,318
Wait till Martha hears about this.

1327
01:17:55,358 --> 01:17:57,158
- What did they have to eat? -
Wha-What did they have to eat?

1328
01:17:57,198 --> 01:18:01,998
H-H-Harry, you should see what
they're cooking up in the town for you.

1329
01:18:02,078 --> 01:18:02,998
Oh, they are?

1330
01:18:03,038 --> 01:18:04,998
The Navy's going to fly
mother home this afternoon.

1331
01:18:05,038 --> 01:18:06,718
In a plane?

1332
01:18:06,758 --> 01:18:08,718
What? Uncle Billy?

1333
01:18:08,758 --> 01:18:10,798
- Has Uncle Billy come in yet?
- No, he stopped at the bank first.

1334
01:18:10,878 --> 01:18:12,838
No, he's not here right
now, Harry. But look...

1335
01:18:12,918 --> 01:18:14,718
- George... ...tell me about it.

1336
01:18:14,758 --> 01:18:16,478
...George, tha-that man's here again.

1337
01:18:16,518 --> 01:18:18,198
- What man? -
B-B-Bank... examiner.

1338
01:18:18,238 --> 01:18:19,598
Oh, oh. Uh, uh,

1339
01:18:19,678 --> 01:18:21,878
Harry, talk to Eustace
for a minute, will you?

1340
01:18:21,918 --> 01:18:23,918
I'll be right back. Well...

1341
01:18:23,958 --> 01:18:25,918
- Harry...
- Good morning, sir.

1342
01:18:25,958 --> 01:18:27,198
Carter, bank examiner.

1343
01:18:27,238 --> 01:18:29,638
- Mr. Carter, Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

1344
01:18:29,718 --> 01:18:31,438
We're all excited around here.

1345
01:18:31,478 --> 01:18:33,478
My brother just got the
Congressional Medal of Honor.

1346
01:18:33,518 --> 01:18:34,958
The president just decorated him.

1347
01:18:35,038 --> 01:18:36,598
Well, I guess they do those things.

1348
01:18:36,678 --> 01:18:38,198
Well, I trust you had a good year.

1349
01:18:38,278 --> 01:18:39,438
Good year?

1350
01:18:39,478 --> 01:18:42,878
Uh, well, between you and
me, Mr. Carter, we're broke.

1351
01:18:42,918 --> 01:18:46,318
Yeah, very funny.

1352
01:18:46,358 --> 01:18:49,158
Uh, w-well... Now, come
right in here, Mr. Carter.

1353
01:18:49,238 --> 01:18:53,758
Oh, I shouldn't wonder when you okay reverse
charges on personal long distance calls.

1354
01:18:53,798 --> 01:18:54,758
George, shall we hang up?

1355
01:18:54,798 --> 01:18:56,958
No, no. He wants to talk to
Uncle Billy. You just hold on.

1356
01:18:56,998 --> 01:18:59,878
Now, if you'll cooperate, I'd
like to finish with you by tonight.

1357
01:18:59,918 --> 01:19:02,678
I want to spend Christmas
in Elmira with my family.

1358
01:19:02,758 --> 01:19:04,078
I don't blame you at all, Mr. Carter.

1359
01:19:04,118 --> 01:19:06,358
Just step right in
here. We'll fix you up.

1360
01:19:06,398 --> 01:19:10,118
December twenty-fourth...

1361
01:19:15,318 --> 01:19:18,238
Eight thousand.

1362
01:19:18,878 --> 01:19:21,358
Merry Christmas, Mr. Potter...

1363
01:19:21,398 --> 01:19:23,798
Well, good morning, Mr. Potter?

1364
01:19:23,838 --> 01:19:25,078
What's the news?

1365
01:19:25,158 --> 01:19:28,838
Oh, well, well, well. Harry
Bailey wins Congressional Medal.

1366
01:19:28,918 --> 01:19:30,958
That couldn't be one
of the Bailey boys?

1367
01:19:30,998 --> 01:19:34,638
You just can't keep those Baileys
down, now can you, Mr. Potter.

1368
01:19:34,678 --> 01:19:37,318
How does slacker
George feel about that?

1369
01:19:37,358 --> 01:19:38,478
Very jealous. Very jealous.

1370
01:19:38,518 --> 01:19:40,798
He only lost three
buttons off his vest.

1371
01:19:40,838 --> 01:19:45,038
Of course, slacker George would have
gotten two of these medals if he had gone.

1372
01:19:45,078 --> 01:19:46,038
Bad ear.

1373
01:19:46,078 --> 01:19:50,278
Yes. After all, Potter, some people
like George had to stay at home.

1374
01:19:50,318 --> 01:19:54,158
Not every heel was
in Germany and Japan.

1375
01:20:01,878 --> 01:20:05,238
- Oh, good morning, Mr. Bailey.
- Good morning, Horace.

1376
01:20:06,598 --> 01:20:09,158
- I guess you forgot something.
- Huh?

1377
01:20:09,198 --> 01:20:11,198
- You forgot something.
- What?

1378
01:20:11,238 --> 01:20:13,878
- Well, aren't you going to make a deposit?
- Oh, sure, sure I am.

1379
01:20:13,918 --> 01:20:16,478
Well, then it's usually customary
to bring the money with you.

1380
01:20:16,558 --> 01:20:20,358
Huh? Oh, shucks...

1381
01:20:20,398 --> 01:20:24,078
Well, I knew I had...

1382
01:20:24,158 --> 01:20:28,038
- How about that finger there?
- Hmm? Well, I...

1383
01:20:28,078 --> 01:20:29,238
Bailey...

1384
01:20:35,918 --> 01:20:38,198
Take me back there. Hurry up.

1385
01:20:40,238 --> 01:20:42,358
Come on, look sharp.

1386
01:21:00,238 --> 01:21:01,398
Take me back.

1387
01:21:11,518 --> 01:21:14,758
Just make yourself at home, Mr.
Carter. I'll get those books for you.

1388
01:21:14,838 --> 01:21:16,238
Oh, hello, Vi.

1389
01:21:16,318 --> 01:21:17,918
George, can I see you for a second?

1390
01:21:17,998 --> 01:21:20,758
Why, of course you can.
Come on in the office here.

1391
01:21:20,798 --> 01:21:23,518
Uncle Billy, talk to Harry.
He's on the telephone.

1392
01:21:24,598 --> 01:21:27,358
Hurry, Uncle Billy, hurry.
Long distance, Washington.

1393
01:21:27,398 --> 01:21:28,558
Hey, here's Harry on the phone.

1394
01:21:28,638 --> 01:21:29,758
Harry, your nephew, remember?

1395
01:21:29,798 --> 01:21:32,198
Here he is. Hurry up.

1396
01:21:32,238 --> 01:21:33,918
Hello... hello.
Y-Y-Yes, Harry.

1397
01:21:33,958 --> 01:21:35,998
Yes... everything...
everything's fine.

1398
01:21:36,878 --> 01:21:39,638
I should have my head examined.
Eight thousand dollars.

1399
01:21:39,718 --> 01:21:41,558
It's got to be somewhere.

1400
01:21:48,078 --> 01:21:49,118
Here you are.

1401
01:21:49,678 --> 01:21:51,358
Character?

1402
01:21:51,398 --> 01:21:52,598
If I had any character, I'd...

1403
01:21:52,638 --> 01:21:56,398
It takes a lot of character to leave
your home town and start all over again.

1404
01:21:56,478 --> 01:21:57,758
No, George, don't...

1405
01:21:57,798 --> 01:22:00,678
- Now here, now you're broke, aren't you?
- I know, but...

1406
01:22:00,758 --> 01:22:03,558
What do you want to do,
hock your furs and that hat?

1407
01:22:04,998 --> 01:22:06,318
Want to walk to New York?

1408
01:22:06,398 --> 01:22:08,078
You know, they charge for
meals and rent up there

1409
01:22:08,158 --> 01:22:09,718
just the same as they
do in Bedford Falls.

1410
01:22:09,758 --> 01:22:11,638
- Yeah, sure.
- It's a loan.

1411
01:22:11,718 --> 01:22:14,318
That's my business. Building and Loan.

1412
01:22:14,398 --> 01:22:16,358
Besides, you'll get a job.

1413
01:22:16,438 --> 01:22:17,398
Good luck to you.

1414
01:22:17,438 --> 01:22:19,758
I'm glad I know you, George Bailey.

1415
01:22:25,038 --> 01:22:26,278
Say hello to New York for me.

1416
01:22:26,318 --> 01:22:27,438
Yeah, yeah... sure, I will.

1417
01:22:27,518 --> 01:22:29,278
Now let's hear from
you once in a while.

1418
01:22:30,318 --> 01:22:31,598
Hmm.

1419
01:22:33,798 --> 01:22:36,918
- Merry Christmas, Violet.
- Merry Christmas, George.

1420
01:22:37,678 --> 01:22:39,238
- Mr. Bailey.
- Oh, Mr. Carter,

1421
01:22:39,318 --> 01:22:40,798
I'm sorry. I'll be right with you.

1422
01:22:40,838 --> 01:22:43,438
- Uncle Billy in?
- Yeah, he's in his office.

1423
01:22:43,478 --> 01:22:45,798
Unc... What's going on?

1424
01:22:45,838 --> 01:22:48,598
The bank examiner's here, and I...

1425
01:22:48,638 --> 01:22:49,918
- He's here?
- Yeah, yeah.

1426
01:22:49,958 --> 01:22:51,718
He wants the accounts payable...

1427
01:22:51,798 --> 01:22:54,598
- What's the matter with you?
- Come here.

1428
01:23:15,478 --> 01:23:16,638
- Eustace.
- Yeah?

1429
01:23:16,678 --> 01:23:17,798
Come here a minute.

1430
01:23:19,518 --> 01:23:21,878
Did you see Uncle Billy
with any cash last night?

1431
01:23:21,918 --> 01:23:24,518
He had it on his desk counting
it before he closed up.

1432
01:23:25,518 --> 01:23:26,998
Now look, did you buy anything?

1433
01:23:27,038 --> 01:23:29,478
- Nothing. Not even a stick of gum.
- All right, all right.

1434
01:23:29,518 --> 01:23:31,838
Now, we'll go over every step
you took since you left the house.

1435
01:23:31,918 --> 01:23:33,278
All right. This way.

1436
01:23:43,358 --> 01:23:45,278
And did you put the
envelope in your pocket?

1437
01:23:45,318 --> 01:23:48,118
Yeah... maybe, maybe, maybe...

1438
01:23:48,198 --> 01:23:49,838
Maybe-Maybe! I don't want any maybe.

1439
01:23:49,878 --> 01:23:51,518
We've got to find that money!

1440
01:23:51,558 --> 01:23:55,078
- I'm no good to you, George. I...
- Uncle Billy, do you...

1441
01:23:56,238 --> 01:24:01,398
Listen to me. Do you have
any secret place hiding place?

1442
01:24:06,478 --> 01:24:09,718
Listen to me, listen
to me! Think! Think!

1443
01:24:09,758 --> 01:24:13,798
I can't think anymore, George.
I can't think anymore. It hurts...

1444
01:24:13,878 --> 01:24:16,838
Where's that money, you
silly, stupid old fool?!

1445
01:24:16,878 --> 01:24:17,958
Where's that money?

1446
01:24:18,038 --> 01:24:19,718
Do you realize what this means?

1447
01:24:19,758 --> 01:24:22,918
It means bankruptcy
and scandal, and prison!

1448
01:24:23,878 --> 01:24:25,158
That's what it means.

1449
01:24:25,198 --> 01:24:26,798
One of us is going to jail!

1450
01:24:26,838 --> 01:24:28,398
Well, it's not gonna be me.

1451
01:24:51,358 --> 01:24:52,398
Hello, darling.

1452
01:24:52,438 --> 01:24:54,158
Hello daddy, hello daddy.

1453
01:24:54,198 --> 01:24:56,398
How do you like it?
We're going to put...

1454
01:24:56,438 --> 01:24:58,318
Bless you!

1455
01:24:59,758 --> 01:25:00,718
Did you bring the wreath?

1456
01:25:00,758 --> 01:25:03,718
- Yes, Daddy, did you bring the Christmas wreath?
- What wreath?

1457
01:25:03,798 --> 01:25:06,318
Oh, that's the Merry Christmas
Wreath for the window.

1458
01:25:06,358 --> 01:25:07,838
No. I left it at the office.

1459
01:25:07,878 --> 01:25:09,918
- Is it snowing?
- Yeah, just started.

1460
01:25:09,958 --> 01:25:13,518
- Where's your coat and hat?
- Left them at the office.

1461
01:25:13,558 --> 01:25:16,438
- What's the matter?
- Nothing's the matter. Everything's all right.

1462
01:25:24,678 --> 01:25:26,678
Go on, Pete, you're a big boy.

1463
01:25:26,758 --> 01:25:27,918
You can put the star up.

1464
01:25:27,998 --> 01:25:29,958
Way up at the top.

1465
01:25:29,998 --> 01:25:31,478
That's it.

1466
01:25:31,518 --> 01:25:32,878
All right.

1467
01:25:32,918 --> 01:25:34,638
Fill in that little
bare spot right there.

1468
01:25:34,678 --> 01:25:35,918
That's it.

1469
01:25:37,958 --> 01:25:39,918
Isn't it wonderful about Harry?

1470
01:25:39,958 --> 01:25:41,238
We're famous, George.

1471
01:25:41,318 --> 01:25:45,318
I'll bet I had fifty calls today
about the parade, the banquet.

1472
01:25:45,398 --> 01:25:47,638
Your mother's so excited, she...

1473
01:26:08,278 --> 01:26:10,438
Must she keep playing that?

1474
01:26:10,518 --> 01:26:13,198
I have to practice it for
the party tonight, Daddy.

1475
01:26:13,238 --> 01:26:16,518
Mommy says we can stay up till
midnight and sing Christmas carols.

1476
01:26:16,558 --> 01:26:17,838
Can you sing, Daddy?

1477
01:26:18,438 --> 01:26:20,238
Better hurry and shave.

1478
01:26:20,278 --> 01:26:21,838
The families will be here soon.

1479
01:26:21,878 --> 01:26:25,358
Families! I... I don't
want the families over here.

1480
01:26:27,318 --> 01:26:30,758
Come on out in the kitchen
with me while I finish dinner.

1481
01:26:30,798 --> 01:26:32,998
Excuse me. Excuse me.

1482
01:26:33,038 --> 01:26:35,158
Have a hectic day?

1483
01:26:35,198 --> 01:26:39,198
Oh, yeah. Another big
red-letter day for the Bailey's.

1484
01:26:39,278 --> 01:26:41,878
Daddy, the Brown's next door
have a new car. You should see it.

1485
01:26:41,918 --> 01:26:44,518
Well, what's the matter with our
car? Isn't it good enough for you?

1486
01:26:44,558 --> 01:26:45,798
Yes, Daddy.

1487
01:26:45,878 --> 01:26:47,758
Excuse me. Excuse me.

1488
01:26:47,838 --> 01:26:49,678
Excuse you for what?

1489
01:26:49,758 --> 01:26:51,038
I burped!

1490
01:26:52,038 --> 01:26:53,278
All right, darling, you're excused.

1491
01:26:53,318 --> 01:26:55,758
Now go upstairs and see
what little Zuzu wants.

1492
01:26:56,758 --> 01:26:58,718
Zuzu. W-What's the matter with Zuzu?

1493
01:26:58,758 --> 01:27:00,598
Oh, she's got a cold. She's in bed.

1494
01:27:00,638 --> 01:27:02,318
Caught it coming home from school.

1495
01:27:02,358 --> 01:27:03,918
They gave her a flower for a prize

1496
01:27:03,998 --> 01:27:06,318
and she didn't want to crush it
so she didn't button up her coat.

1497
01:27:06,358 --> 01:27:07,998
- What is it, a sore throat or what?
- Just a cold.

1498
01:27:08,038 --> 01:27:09,878
- The doctor says it's nothing serious.
- The doctor?

1499
01:27:09,918 --> 01:27:11,638
- Was the doctor here?
- Yes, I called him right away.

1500
01:27:11,718 --> 01:27:13,438
- He says it's nothing to worry about.
- Is she running a temperature?

1501
01:27:13,478 --> 01:27:15,798
- What is it? - Just a
teensy one, ninety-nine, six.

1502
01:27:15,838 --> 01:27:18,038
- She'll be all right.
- Gosh, it's this old house.

1503
01:27:18,078 --> 01:27:20,398
I don't... I don't know why
we don't all have pneumonia.

1504
01:27:20,438 --> 01:27:25,118
This drafty old barn! Might as
well be living in a refrigerator.

1505
01:27:25,158 --> 01:27:29,918
Why did we have to live here in the first place
and stay around this measly, crummy old town?

1506
01:27:30,918 --> 01:27:31,998
George, what's wrong?

1507
01:27:32,038 --> 01:27:33,358
Wrong? Everything's wrong.

1508
01:27:33,398 --> 01:27:34,598
You call this a happy family?

1509
01:27:34,638 --> 01:27:36,518
Why did we have to
have all these kids?

1510
01:27:36,558 --> 01:27:38,598
Dad, how do you spell 'frankincense'?

1511
01:27:38,638 --> 01:27:40,558
I don't know. Why, ask your mother.

1512
01:27:40,598 --> 01:27:42,638
- Where're you going?
- Going up to see Zuzu.

1513
01:27:42,678 --> 01:27:44,758
He told me to write
a play for tomorrow.

1514
01:27:55,718 --> 01:27:59,718
F-R-A-N-K-I-N...

1515
01:27:59,758 --> 01:28:01,158
Hi, Daddy.

1516
01:28:02,278 --> 01:28:04,958
- Well, what happened to you?
- I won a flower.

1517
01:28:04,998 --> 01:28:07,638
Wait now. W-Where do
you think you're going?

1518
01:28:07,678 --> 01:28:09,238
Want to give my flower a drink.

1519
01:28:09,278 --> 01:28:11,798
All right, all right, here,
give Daddy the flower.

1520
01:28:11,878 --> 01:28:14,478
I'll give it a drink. All right, here.

1521
01:28:15,958 --> 01:28:21,038
- Look, Daddy... paste it.
- Yeah, all right...

1522
01:28:24,838 --> 01:28:26,918
Now, I'll paste this together.

1523
01:28:30,478 --> 01:28:35,918
Now, there it is, good as new.
All right, give the flower a drink.

1524
01:28:35,958 --> 01:28:38,278
- Now, will you do something for me?
- What?

1525
01:28:38,318 --> 01:28:40,278
Will you try to get some sleep?

1526
01:28:40,318 --> 01:28:43,118
I'm not sleepy. I want
to look at my flower.

1527
01:28:43,198 --> 01:28:45,878
I know, I know, but
you just go to sleep

1528
01:28:45,958 --> 01:28:50,398
and then you can dream about
it, and it'll be a whole garden.

1529
01:28:50,438 --> 01:28:52,558
- It will?
- Uh-huh.

1530
01:29:00,038 --> 01:29:03,158
- Telephone!
- I'll get it.

1531
01:29:05,358 --> 01:29:07,238
Hello.

1532
01:29:07,278 --> 01:29:09,558
Yes, this is Mrs. Bailey.

1533
01:29:09,598 --> 01:29:12,718
Oh, thank you, Mrs. Welch.
I'm sure she'll be all right.

1534
01:29:12,758 --> 01:29:15,518
The doctor says that she ought to be out
of bed in time to have her Christmas dinner.

1535
01:29:15,558 --> 01:29:17,198
- Is that Zuzu's teacher?
- Yes.

1536
01:29:17,238 --> 01:29:18,558
Let me speak to her.

1537
01:29:18,638 --> 01:29:21,518
Hello. Hello, Mrs. Welch?

1538
01:29:21,558 --> 01:29:23,638
This is George Bailey.
I'm Zuzu's father.

1539
01:29:23,678 --> 01:29:25,678
Say, what kind of a
teacher are you anyway?

1540
01:29:25,718 --> 01:29:28,078
What do you mean sending her
home like that, half naked?

1541
01:29:28,118 --> 01:29:30,278
Do you realize she'll probably end
up with pneumonia on account of you?

1542
01:29:30,318 --> 01:29:31,718
- George!
- Is this the sort of thing

1543
01:29:31,798 --> 01:29:34,758
we pay taxes for
- to have teachers... to have teachers like you?

1544
01:29:34,798 --> 01:29:38,318
Stupid, silly, careless people who send
our kids home without any clothes on?

1545
01:29:38,398 --> 01:29:40,318
You know, maybe my kids
aren't the best-dressed kids,

1546
01:29:40,358 --> 01:29:42,118
and maybe they don't
have any decent clothes...

1547
01:29:42,158 --> 01:29:44,198
Aw, that stupid...

1548
01:29:44,238 --> 01:29:47,718
He-Hello, Mrs. Welch.
I-I-I want to apologize.

1549
01:29:47,798 --> 01:29:50,518
Hel-lo... hello...

1550
01:29:51,558 --> 01:29:54,118
- She's hung up.
- I-I-I'll hang her up.

1551
01:29:54,198 --> 01:29:56,118
Now, who do you think you are?

1552
01:29:56,198 --> 01:29:57,278
What is that?

1553
01:29:57,318 --> 01:29:59,118
Hello? Who is this?

1554
01:29:59,158 --> 01:30:01,078
Oh, Mr. Welch?

1555
01:30:01,118 --> 01:30:02,518
Okay, that's fine, Mr. Welch.

1556
01:30:02,598 --> 01:30:04,758
Gives me a chance to tell you
what I really think of your wife.

1557
01:30:04,838 --> 01:30:07,758
- George...
- Will you get out and let me handle this?

1558
01:30:07,798 --> 01:30:09,238
Hello?

1559
01:30:09,318 --> 01:30:13,598
Hello? What? Oh, you will, huh?

1560
01:30:13,678 --> 01:30:16,678
Okay, Mr. Welch. Any time
you think you're man enough.

1561
01:30:16,758 --> 01:30:20,398
Hello... any...

1562
01:30:20,438 --> 01:30:21,878
Oh...

1563
01:30:21,958 --> 01:30:23,318
Daddy, how do you spell "Hallelujah?"

1564
01:30:23,398 --> 01:30:25,318
How should I know? What do
you think I am, a dictionary?

1565
01:30:25,358 --> 01:30:26,838
Tommy, stop that! Stop it!

1566
01:30:26,878 --> 01:30:30,078
Janie, haven't you leaned that silly tune
yet? You've played it over and over again.

1567
01:30:30,118 --> 01:30:31,798
Now stop it! Stop it!

1568
01:30:59,638 --> 01:31:01,478
I'm sorry, Mary.

1569
01:31:04,438 --> 01:31:06,038
Janie, I'm sorry.

1570
01:31:07,198 --> 01:31:09,318
I didn't mean...

1571
01:31:09,918 --> 01:31:11,958
You go on and practice.

1572
01:31:16,758 --> 01:31:20,638
Pete, I owe you an apology, too.

1573
01:31:20,678 --> 01:31:22,118
I'm sorry.

1574
01:31:23,278 --> 01:31:24,798
What do you want to know?

1575
01:31:24,838 --> 01:31:26,158
Nothing, Daddy.

1576
01:31:33,038 --> 01:31:34,758
What's the matter with everybody?

1577
01:31:34,798 --> 01:31:37,198
Janie, go on. I told you to practice.

1578
01:31:37,238 --> 01:31:39,558
- Now, go on, play.
- Oh, Daddy...

1579
01:31:44,318 --> 01:31:45,878
George, why must you
torture the children?

1580
01:31:45,918 --> 01:31:47,158
Why don't you...

1581
01:31:48,558 --> 01:31:49,718
Mary...

1582
01:32:03,958 --> 01:32:05,638
Bedford
two-four-seven, please.

1583
01:32:05,678 --> 01:32:07,798
- Is Daddy in trouble?
- Yes, Pete.

1584
01:32:07,838 --> 01:32:11,078
- Shall I pray for him?
- Yes, Janie, pray very hard.

1585
01:32:11,118 --> 01:32:14,078
- Me, too?
- You, too, Tommy.

1586
01:32:14,118 --> 01:32:16,598
Hello, Uncle Billy?

1587
01:32:16,638 --> 01:32:19,158
I'm in trouble, Mr. Potter.

1588
01:32:19,198 --> 01:32:21,398
I need help.

1589
01:32:21,438 --> 01:32:24,318
Through some sort of an accident my
company's short in their accounts.

1590
01:32:24,358 --> 01:32:26,278
The bank examiner's got there today.

1591
01:32:26,318 --> 01:32:28,478
I've got to raise eight
thousand dollars immediately.

1592
01:32:28,518 --> 01:32:31,118
Oh, so that's what the reporters
wanted to talk to you about?

1593
01:32:31,158 --> 01:32:32,438
- The reporters?
- Yes,

1594
01:32:32,478 --> 01:32:36,158
they called me up from
your Building and Loan.

1595
01:32:36,198 --> 01:32:39,798
Oh, there's a man over there
from the D.A.'s office, too.

1596
01:32:39,878 --> 01:32:40,958
He's looking for you.

1597
01:32:40,998 --> 01:32:42,838
Please help me, Mr. Potter.

1598
01:32:42,878 --> 01:32:44,638
Help me, won't you, please?

1599
01:32:44,678 --> 01:32:46,518
Can't you see what
it means to my family?

1600
01:32:46,558 --> 01:32:49,518
I'll pay any sort of a bonus
on the loan, any interest

1601
01:32:49,558 --> 01:32:51,198
if you still want the
Building and Loan. I'm...

1602
01:32:51,238 --> 01:32:54,878
George, could it possibly be there's
a slight discrepancy in the books?

1603
01:32:54,958 --> 01:32:56,358
No, sir. There's nothing
wrong with the books.

1604
01:32:56,438 --> 01:32:57,798
I've just misplaced
eight thousand dollars.

1605
01:32:57,838 --> 01:32:59,478
I can't find it anywhere.

1606
01:32:59,518 --> 01:33:02,758
You misplaced eight thousand dollars?

1607
01:33:02,798 --> 01:33:03,838
Yes, sir.

1608
01:33:06,678 --> 01:33:08,358
Have you notified the police?

1609
01:33:08,398 --> 01:33:10,238
No, sir. I-I didn't
want the publicity.

1610
01:33:10,278 --> 01:33:12,358
Harry's homecoming tomorrow...

1611
01:33:12,398 --> 01:33:14,598
They're gonna believe that one.

1612
01:33:14,638 --> 01:33:16,758
What've you been doing, George?

1613
01:33:16,798 --> 01:33:18,478
Playing the market with
the company's money?

1614
01:33:18,558 --> 01:33:20,158
No, sir, no, sir. I haven't.

1615
01:33:20,198 --> 01:33:21,718
What is it, a woman then?

1616
01:33:21,758 --> 01:33:25,838
You know, it's all over town that
you've been giving money to Violet Bick.

1617
01:33:25,878 --> 01:33:28,198
- What!
- Not that it makes any difference to me,

1618
01:33:28,238 --> 01:33:29,398
but why did you come to me?

1619
01:33:29,438 --> 01:33:32,198
Why don't you go to Sam Wainwright
and ask him for the money?

1620
01:33:32,278 --> 01:33:33,838
I can't get ahold of
him. He's in Europe.

1621
01:33:33,878 --> 01:33:35,358
Well, what about all
your other friends?

1622
01:33:35,398 --> 01:33:37,158
They don't have that
kind of money, Mr. Potter.

1623
01:33:37,198 --> 01:33:39,638
You know that. You're the only
one in town that can help me.

1624
01:33:39,678 --> 01:33:41,478
I see.

1625
01:33:41,518 --> 01:33:45,078
I've suddenly become quite important.

1626
01:33:45,118 --> 01:33:47,998
Wha-What kind of security
would I have, George?

1627
01:33:48,078 --> 01:33:51,238
- Have you got any stocks?
- No, sir.

1628
01:33:51,318 --> 01:33:54,158
Bonds? Real estate?
Collateral of any kind?

1629
01:33:54,678 --> 01:33:58,998
I have some life insurance, a
fifteen thousand dollar policy.

1630
01:33:59,038 --> 01:34:01,238
Yes... how much is your equity in it?

1631
01:34:01,278 --> 01:34:05,078
- Five hundred dollars.
- Five hundred dollars!

1632
01:34:05,118 --> 01:34:09,358
And you ask me to lend
you eight thousand.

1633
01:34:09,398 --> 01:34:10,438
Look at you.

1634
01:34:10,478 --> 01:34:12,678
You used to be so cocky!

1635
01:34:12,718 --> 01:34:17,278
You were going to go out
and conquer the world.

1636
01:34:17,358 --> 01:34:21,558
You once called me a
warped, frustrated old man.

1637
01:34:21,598 --> 01:34:25,718
What are you but a warped
frustrated young man?

1638
01:34:25,758 --> 01:34:31,198
A miserable little clerk crawling in here
on your hands and knees and begging for help.

1639
01:34:31,238 --> 01:34:33,238
No securities, no stocks, no bonds,

1640
01:34:33,278 --> 01:34:39,958
nothing but a miserable little five hundred
dollar equity in a life insurance policy.

1641
01:34:40,038 --> 01:34:42,798
You're worth more dead than alive.

1642
01:34:42,878 --> 01:34:46,038
Why don't you go to the
riff-raff you love so much

1643
01:34:46,078 --> 01:34:48,958
ask them to let you
have eight thousand?

1644
01:34:48,998 --> 01:34:50,118
You know why?

1645
01:34:50,198 --> 01:34:52,878
Because they'd run you
out of town on a rail.

1646
01:34:52,918 --> 01:34:56,238
But I tell you what I'm
going to do for you, George.

1647
01:34:56,278 --> 01:34:59,238
Since the state
examiner is still here,

1648
01:34:59,278 --> 01:35:02,078
as a stock holder of
the Building and Loan,

1649
01:35:02,158 --> 01:35:05,478
I'm going to swear out a
warrant for your arrest.

1650
01:35:05,558 --> 01:35:10,198
Misappropriation of funds,
manipulation, malfeasance...

1651
01:35:11,078 --> 01:35:13,558
All right, George, go ahead, George.

1652
01:35:13,598 --> 01:35:16,718
You can't hide in a
little town like this.

1653
01:35:16,758 --> 01:35:19,158
Bill? This is Potter.

1654
01:35:31,958 --> 01:35:34,838
Joe! Merry Christmas!

1655
01:35:34,918 --> 01:35:36,518
- Glad you come.
- Thank you.

1656
01:35:36,558 --> 01:35:39,318
- How about some of that good spaghetti?
- We got everything.

1657
01:35:51,118 --> 01:35:52,758
God...

1658
01:35:55,758 --> 01:35:56,998
Oh, God...

1659
01:36:01,838 --> 01:36:03,758
Dear Father in Heaven,

1660
01:36:06,918 --> 01:36:11,038
I'm not a praying man,
but if you're up there,

1661
01:36:11,078 --> 01:36:16,718
and you can hear me, show me the way.

1662
01:36:16,758 --> 01:36:20,878
I'm at the end of my rope. I...

1663
01:36:20,918 --> 01:36:23,558
Show me the way, God.

1664
01:36:28,038 --> 01:36:29,678
Are you all right, George?

1665
01:36:29,718 --> 01:36:31,318
Want someone to take you home?

1666
01:36:34,118 --> 01:36:36,478
Why you drink so much, my friend?

1667
01:36:36,518 --> 01:36:40,398
Please go home, Mr. Bailey.
This is Christmas Eve.

1668
01:36:40,438 --> 01:36:43,118
Bailey? Which Bailey?

1669
01:36:43,198 --> 01:36:45,838
This is Mr. George Bailey.

1670
01:36:49,918 --> 01:36:52,718
And the next time you talk to my
wife like that, you'll get worse.

1671
01:36:52,798 --> 01:36:54,198
She cried for an hour.

1672
01:36:54,238 --> 01:36:56,438
It isn't enough she slaves
teaching your stupid kids

1673
01:36:56,478 --> 01:36:58,638
how to read and write, and
you have to bawl her out, eh.

1674
01:36:58,678 --> 01:36:59,838
You get out of here, Mr. Welch!

1675
01:36:59,878 --> 01:37:01,358
Now wait. I want to pay for my drink.

1676
01:37:01,398 --> 01:37:03,918
Never mind the money.
You get out of here quick.

1677
01:37:03,998 --> 01:37:06,478
- All right.
- You hit my best friend. Get out!

1678
01:37:11,758 --> 01:37:13,518
You all right, George?

1679
01:37:13,558 --> 01:37:14,598
Who was that?

1680
01:37:14,678 --> 01:37:16,798
He gone. No worry.

1681
01:37:16,878 --> 01:37:19,478
His name is Welch. He no
come in to my place no more.

1682
01:37:19,558 --> 01:37:22,718
Oh, Welch. That's
what I get for praying.

1683
01:37:22,798 --> 01:37:24,798
The last time he come in
here. You hear that, Nick?

1684
01:37:24,878 --> 01:37:25,958
Yes, you bet.

1685
01:37:26,038 --> 01:37:29,638
Where's my insurance policy? Oh, here.

1686
01:37:29,678 --> 01:37:31,558
- Oh, no, please, no go out this way, Mr. Bailey.
- I'm all right.

1687
01:37:31,598 --> 01:37:34,118
No, no, you no feel so
good. Sit down and rest.

1688
01:37:34,158 --> 01:37:36,598
- I'm all right.
- Please no go away. Please!

1689
01:37:55,198 --> 01:37:56,478
What do you think you're doing?

1690
01:37:59,598 --> 01:38:00,998
Now look what you did.

1691
01:38:01,038 --> 01:38:03,358
My great-grandfather
planted this tree.

1692
01:38:04,278 --> 01:38:06,358
Hey, you! Hey, you!

1693
01:38:07,038 --> 01:38:08,798
Come back here, you drunken fool!

1694
01:38:08,878 --> 01:38:10,638
Get this car out of here!

1695
01:38:18,718 --> 01:38:20,958
Hey, what's the matter with
you? Look where you're going!

1696
01:39:09,118 --> 01:39:10,598
Help!

1697
01:39:11,838 --> 01:39:16,398
Help! Help! Help!

1698
01:39:18,158 --> 01:39:20,718
Help! Help!

1699
01:39:22,478 --> 01:39:24,718
Help!

1700
01:39:26,958 --> 01:39:31,318
Help! Help! Help! Help!

1701
01:39:33,518 --> 01:39:34,878
Help!

1702
01:39:35,998 --> 01:39:40,118
Help! Help! Help!

1703
01:39:56,931 --> 01:39:59,211
I didn't have time to get
some stylish underwear.

1704
01:39:59,291 --> 01:40:01,691
My wife gave me this
on my last birthday.

1705
01:40:02,731 --> 01:40:04,571
I passed away in it.

1706
01:40:08,051 --> 01:40:10,771
Oh, Tom Sawyer's drying out, too.

1707
01:40:14,131 --> 01:40:16,931
You should read the new book
Mark Twain's writing now.

1708
01:40:18,171 --> 01:40:20,091
How did you happen to fall in?

1709
01:40:20,131 --> 01:40:23,651
I didn't fall in. I
jumped in to save George.

1710
01:40:23,731 --> 01:40:26,691
You what? To... to save me?

1711
01:40:26,771 --> 01:40:29,931
Well, I did, didn't I? You didn't
go through with it, did you?

1712
01:40:30,011 --> 01:40:32,091
- Go through with what?
- Suicide.

1713
01:40:32,171 --> 01:40:35,331
Well, it's against the law
to commit suicide around here.

1714
01:40:35,411 --> 01:40:38,211
Yeah, it's against the
law where I come from, too.

1715
01:40:38,251 --> 01:40:41,011
- Where do you come from?
- Heaven.

1716
01:40:45,771 --> 01:40:48,531
I had to act quickly.
That's why I jumped in.

1717
01:40:48,571 --> 01:40:51,491
I knew if I were drowning
you'd try to save me.

1718
01:40:51,571 --> 01:40:54,451
And you see, you did, and
that's how I saved you.

1719
01:40:54,491 --> 01:40:56,571
Very funny.

1720
01:40:56,611 --> 01:40:58,651
Your lip's bleeding, George.

1721
01:40:58,691 --> 01:41:02,971
Yeah, I got a bust in the jaw in
answer to a prayer a little bit ago.

1722
01:41:03,011 --> 01:41:06,851
Oh, no, no, no, George, I'm
the answer to your prayer.

1723
01:41:06,891 --> 01:41:08,891
That's why I was sent down here.

1724
01:41:10,568 --> 01:41:12,008
How do you know my name?

1725
01:41:12,048 --> 01:41:15,648
Oh, I know all about you. I've
watched you grow up from a little boy.

1726
01:41:15,688 --> 01:41:19,408
- What are you, a mind reader or something?
- Oh, no.

1727
01:41:19,448 --> 01:41:23,128
- Well, who are you then?
- Clarence Odbody, A-S-2.

1728
01:41:23,168 --> 01:41:27,808
Odbody... A-S-2.
Wh-Wh-What's that A-S-2?

1729
01:41:27,888 --> 01:41:29,368
Angel Second Class.

1730
01:41:40,008 --> 01:41:41,728
Cheerio, my good man.

1731
01:41:45,888 --> 01:41:47,368
Oh, brother...

1732
01:41:52,088 --> 01:41:54,288
I wonder what Martini
put in those drinks?

1733
01:41:56,808 --> 01:41:59,128
Hey, what's... with you...

1734
01:41:59,208 --> 01:42:01,648
wh-wh-what-did you
say just a minute ago?

1735
01:42:01,688 --> 01:42:03,288
Why'd you want to save me?

1736
01:42:03,328 --> 01:42:07,448
That's what I was sent down
for. I'm your guardian angel.

1737
01:42:07,488 --> 01:42:09,528
I wouldn't be a bit surprised.

1738
01:42:09,608 --> 01:42:12,648
Ridiculous of you to think
of killing yourself for money.

1739
01:42:12,688 --> 01:42:15,448
- Eight thousand dollars.
- Yeah, I'll say. Just things like that.

1740
01:42:15,488 --> 01:42:17,128
Now how do you know that?

1741
01:42:17,168 --> 01:42:19,008
I told you. I'm your guardian angel.

1742
01:42:19,048 --> 01:42:20,808
I know everything about you.

1743
01:42:22,168 --> 01:42:25,368
Well, you look about like
the kind of an angel I'd get.

1744
01:42:25,448 --> 01:42:27,248
Sort of a fallen angel, aren't you?

1745
01:42:27,288 --> 01:42:28,368
What happened to your wings?

1746
01:42:28,408 --> 01:42:32,048
I haven't won my wings yet. That's
why I'm an angel second class.

1747
01:42:36,808 --> 01:42:40,248
I don't know whether I like it very much being
seen around with an angel without any wings.

1748
01:42:40,288 --> 01:42:44,008
Oh, I-I've got to earn them
and you'll help me, won't you?

1749
01:42:44,048 --> 01:42:48,848
- Sure, sure. How?
- By letting me help you.

1750
01:42:50,528 --> 01:42:51,528
Only one way you can help me.

1751
01:42:51,608 --> 01:42:53,648
Y-You don't happen to have
eight thousand bucks on you?

1752
01:42:53,688 --> 01:42:56,248
Oh, no, no. We don't
use money in heaven.

1753
01:42:56,288 --> 01:42:58,888
Oh, that's right, I keep forgetting.

1754
01:42:58,928 --> 01:43:01,448
Comes in pretty handy down here, bub.

1755
01:43:01,528 --> 01:43:04,168
Oh, tut, tut, tut.

1756
01:43:04,248 --> 01:43:06,608
I found it out a little late.

1757
01:43:06,648 --> 01:43:08,888
I'm worth more dead than alive.

1758
01:43:08,968 --> 01:43:13,168
Now look, you mustn't talk like that.
I won't get my wings with that attitude.

1759
01:43:13,248 --> 01:43:15,728
You just don't know
all that you've done.

1760
01:43:15,768 --> 01:43:16,848
If it hadn't been for you...

1761
01:43:16,928 --> 01:43:19,808
Yeah, if it hadn't been for me,
everybody'd be a lot better off.

1762
01:43:19,848 --> 01:43:21,848
My wife, and my kids, and my friends.

1763
01:43:21,888 --> 01:43:25,208
And my... Look, little fellow, why, you
go off and haunt somebody else, will you?

1764
01:43:25,248 --> 01:43:27,968
No, no, you don't
understand. I've got my job.

1765
01:43:28,008 --> 01:43:29,808
Aw, shut up, will you?

1766
01:43:33,968 --> 01:43:37,048
Hmmm, this isn't gonna be so easy.

1767
01:43:41,408 --> 01:43:46,328
Yeah! So you still think killing yourself
would make everyone feel happier, eh?

1768
01:43:47,768 --> 01:43:50,168
Oh, I don't know. I
guess you're right.

1769
01:43:51,888 --> 01:43:54,888
I suppose it would have been better
if I'd never been born at all.

1770
01:43:54,968 --> 01:43:58,328
- What'd you say?
- I said I wish I'd never been born.

1771
01:43:58,408 --> 01:44:01,248
Oh, you mustn't say things like that.

1772
01:44:01,288 --> 01:44:02,528
You...

1773
01:44:02,568 --> 01:44:04,728
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

1774
01:44:04,808 --> 01:44:06,848
That's an idea.

1775
01:44:06,888 --> 01:44:11,648
What do you think?
Yeah, that'll do it.

1776
01:44:11,688 --> 01:44:12,768
All right.

1777
01:44:15,768 --> 01:44:17,488
You've got your wish.

1778
01:44:17,568 --> 01:44:19,248
You've never been born.

1779
01:44:24,328 --> 01:44:26,728
You don't have to make
all that fuss about it.

1780
01:44:28,488 --> 01:44:29,848
What did you say?

1781
01:44:29,928 --> 01:44:32,488
You've never been
born. You don't exist.

1782
01:44:32,528 --> 01:44:33,728
You haven't a care in the world.

1783
01:44:33,768 --> 01:44:37,288
No worries, no obligations, no
eight thousand dollars to get,

1784
01:44:37,328 --> 01:44:39,088
no Potter looking for
you with the sheriff.

1785
01:44:39,128 --> 01:44:41,968
- Say something else in that ear.
- Sure. You can hear out of it.

1786
01:44:42,728 --> 01:44:45,008
Well, that's the doggonedest thing.

1787
01:44:45,048 --> 01:44:47,528
I haven't heard anything out
of that ear since I was a kid.

1788
01:44:47,568 --> 01:44:49,768
Must have been that
jump in that cold water.

1789
01:44:49,848 --> 01:44:52,008
Your lip's stopped
bleeding, too, George.

1790
01:44:57,328 --> 01:44:58,848
What do you know about that?

1791
01:45:00,008 --> 01:45:01,088
What's happened?

1792
01:45:02,368 --> 01:45:04,848
It's stopped snowing out, hasn't it?

1793
01:45:04,928 --> 01:45:07,328
Well, I, uh... What's happened here?

1794
01:45:07,368 --> 01:45:09,168
What I need is a couple
of good stiff drinks.

1795
01:45:09,208 --> 01:45:11,208
How about you, angel,
you want a drink?

1796
01:45:13,248 --> 01:45:15,288
Come on, soon as these
clothes of ours are dry...

1797
01:45:15,328 --> 01:45:17,488
Those are dry.

1798
01:45:17,528 --> 01:45:19,008
What do you know about that?

1799
01:45:19,048 --> 01:45:20,408
Stove's hotter than I thought.

1800
01:45:20,448 --> 01:45:23,888
Now, come on, get your clothes on, and
we'll stroll up to my car and get...

1801
01:45:23,928 --> 01:45:26,328
Oh, I'm sorry. I'll stroll, you fly.

1802
01:45:26,408 --> 01:45:28,728
I can't fly. I haven't got my wings.

1803
01:45:28,768 --> 01:45:30,608
You haven't got your
wings. Yeah, that's right.

1804
01:45:37,208 --> 01:45:38,408
What's the matter?

1805
01:45:38,448 --> 01:45:41,328
Well, this is where I left
my car and it isn't here.

1806
01:45:41,368 --> 01:45:42,528
You have no car.

1807
01:45:42,568 --> 01:45:46,368
Well, I had a car and it was right
here. I guess somebody moved it.

1808
01:45:46,408 --> 01:45:49,048
- Good evening.
- Oh, say... Hey...

1809
01:45:49,128 --> 01:45:50,688
wh-where's my car.

1810
01:45:50,768 --> 01:45:52,688
- I beg your pardon?
- My car, my car.

1811
01:45:52,728 --> 01:45:55,208
I'm the fellow that owns the
car that ran into your tree.

1812
01:45:55,248 --> 01:45:57,248
What tree? What do
you mean, what tree?

1813
01:45:57,288 --> 01:45:59,448
This tree. Here. I ran into it.

1814
01:45:59,528 --> 01:46:03,368
Cut a big gash in
the side of it there.

1815
01:46:07,048 --> 01:46:09,408
You must mean two other trees.

1816
01:46:09,448 --> 01:46:10,568
You had me worried.

1817
01:46:10,648 --> 01:46:13,208
One of the oldest
trees in Pottersville.

1818
01:46:13,248 --> 01:46:15,768
Pottersville. Why,
you mean Bedford Falls.

1819
01:46:15,808 --> 01:46:17,568
I mean Pottersville.

1820
01:46:17,608 --> 01:46:19,568
Don't you think I know where I live?

1821
01:46:19,608 --> 01:46:20,848
What's the matter with you?

1822
01:46:27,488 --> 01:46:30,808
Oh, I don't know. Either
I'm off my nut, or he is.

1823
01:46:30,848 --> 01:46:32,008
...or you are.

1824
01:46:32,768 --> 01:46:34,208
It isn't me!

1825
01:46:34,248 --> 01:46:37,848
Well, maybe I left the car up at
Martini's. Well, come on, Gabriel.

1826
01:46:37,928 --> 01:46:40,088
- Clarence!
- Clarence! Clarence!

1827
01:46:46,168 --> 01:46:48,248
That's all right. Go on in.

1828
01:46:48,288 --> 01:46:50,288
Martini is a friend of mine.

1829
01:46:50,328 --> 01:46:52,248
There's a place to sit down, sit down.

1830
01:46:59,288 --> 01:47:01,568
Oh, hello, Nick. Hey, where's Martini?

1831
01:47:01,608 --> 01:47:03,768
- You want a Martini?
- No, no, Martini.

1832
01:47:03,808 --> 01:47:06,168
- Your boss. Where is he?
- Look, I'm the boss.

1833
01:47:06,208 --> 01:47:07,408
You want a drink or don't you?

1834
01:47:07,448 --> 01:47:09,808
Okay, all right. Double
bourbon, will you? Quick, huh.

1835
01:47:09,888 --> 01:47:11,008
Okay.

1836
01:47:14,208 --> 01:47:15,728
What's yours?

1837
01:47:15,808 --> 01:47:17,328
I was just thinking.

1838
01:47:17,408 --> 01:47:21,048
Uh... It's been so long since I...

1839
01:47:21,088 --> 01:47:24,648
Look, Mister, I'm standing here
waiting for you to make up your mind.

1840
01:47:24,688 --> 01:47:26,208
That's a good man.

1841
01:47:26,288 --> 01:47:32,928
I was just thinking, uh,
of a flaming rum punch.

1842
01:47:32,968 --> 01:47:35,488
No, it's not cold enough for
that. Not nearly cold enough.

1843
01:47:35,528 --> 01:47:36,728
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

1844
01:47:36,808 --> 01:47:38,608
I got it.

1845
01:47:38,648 --> 01:47:42,288
Mulled wine, heavy on the
cinnamon and light on the cloves.

1846
01:47:42,328 --> 01:47:44,168
Off with you, me lad, and be lively!

1847
01:47:44,208 --> 01:47:49,128
Hey, look, Mister, we serve hard drinks
in here for men who want to get drunk fast.

1848
01:47:49,168 --> 01:47:54,008
And we don't need any characters around to
give the joint atmosphere. Is that clear?

1849
01:47:54,048 --> 01:47:56,688
Or do I have to slip you
my left for a convincer?

1850
01:47:56,768 --> 01:47:57,808
What's he talking about?

1851
01:47:57,848 --> 01:48:03,328
Nick, Nick, just give him
the same as mine. He's okay.

1852
01:48:03,368 --> 01:48:04,528
Okay.

1853
01:48:05,928 --> 01:48:07,328
What's the matter with him?

1854
01:48:07,368 --> 01:48:09,488
I never saw Nick act like that before.

1855
01:48:09,528 --> 01:48:12,968
You'll see a lot of
strange things from now on.

1856
01:48:13,008 --> 01:48:14,408
Oh, yeah.

1857
01:48:15,688 --> 01:48:21,088
Hey, li-li-little
fellow, you worry me.

1858
01:48:21,128 --> 01:48:24,608
- You know, y-y-you got
someplace to sleep? - No.

1859
01:48:24,688 --> 01:48:26,208
You don't, huh?

1860
01:48:26,248 --> 01:48:28,848
- Well, y-y-you
got any money? - No.

1861
01:48:28,888 --> 01:48:31,408
No wonder you jumped in the river.

1862
01:48:31,448 --> 01:48:35,048
I jumped in the river to save
you so I could get my wings.

1863
01:48:35,088 --> 01:48:37,088
- Oh, that's
right. - Oh-oh.

1864
01:48:39,088 --> 01:48:41,128
- Somebody's just made it.
- Made what?

1865
01:48:41,168 --> 01:48:45,688
Every time you hear a bell ring, it means
that some angel's just got his wings.

1866
01:48:51,008 --> 01:48:58,328
Look, I think maybe you better not
mention getting your wings around here.

1867
01:48:58,408 --> 01:49:01,448
Why? Don't they believe in angels?

1868
01:49:01,488 --> 01:49:04,448
A... Yeah, they believe in angels.

1869
01:49:04,488 --> 01:49:07,368
Oh, oh! Why should they be
surprised when they see one?

1870
01:49:10,128 --> 01:49:13,808
Aw, he never grew up. He's...

1871
01:49:13,848 --> 01:49:15,728
How old are you, anyway, Clarence?

1872
01:49:15,808 --> 01:49:21,048
Two hundred and
ninety-three, uh, next May.

1873
01:49:21,728 --> 01:49:23,128
That does it!

1874
01:49:23,168 --> 01:49:26,608
Out you two pixies go, through
the door or out the window.

1875
01:49:26,648 --> 01:49:27,768
Look, Nick, what's wrong?

1876
01:49:27,808 --> 01:49:30,808
And that's another thing. Where
do you come off calling me Nick?

1877
01:49:30,848 --> 01:49:32,288
Well, Nick, that's your name.

1878
01:49:32,328 --> 01:49:36,608
What's that got to do with it? I
don't know you from Adam's off ox.

1879
01:49:36,688 --> 01:49:39,208
Hey! Hey, you, rummy
there! Come here! Come here!

1880
01:49:43,008 --> 01:49:46,128
Didn't I tell you never to come
panhandling around here, huh?

1881
01:49:53,688 --> 01:49:55,088
Mr. Gower!

1882
01:49:56,248 --> 01:49:57,488
Mr. Gower!

1883
01:49:59,208 --> 01:50:01,288
What... what is he...

1884
01:50:01,328 --> 01:50:03,768
Mr. Gower! This is George Bailey!

1885
01:50:05,088 --> 01:50:08,328
- Don't you know me?
- No. No.

1886
01:50:08,408 --> 01:50:11,608
Throw 'em out. Throw 'em out!

1887
01:50:11,648 --> 01:50:14,768
Mr. Gower... Hey, what is...

1888
01:50:14,808 --> 01:50:17,048
Hey, Nick, Nick... Isn't
that Mr. Gower, the druggist?

1889
01:50:17,128 --> 01:50:19,288
You know, that's another
reason for me not to like you.

1890
01:50:19,328 --> 01:50:22,848
That rum head spent twenty years
in jail for poisoning a kid.

1891
01:50:22,888 --> 01:50:25,448
If you know him, you must
be a jailbird yourself.

1892
01:50:25,488 --> 01:50:28,008
Uh, would you show these
gentlemen to the door?

1893
01:50:28,048 --> 01:50:29,968
Sure. This way, gentlemen.

1894
01:50:35,688 --> 01:50:37,608
Stay out! Stay out!

1895
01:50:37,648 --> 01:50:38,848
Hey! Get me!

1896
01:50:39,288 --> 01:50:40,808
I'm giving out wings!

1897
01:50:43,288 --> 01:50:44,888
You see, George, you were not there

1898
01:50:44,928 --> 01:50:47,448
to stop Gower from putting
that poison into the capsule...

1899
01:50:47,488 --> 01:50:50,448
What do you mean I wasn't there?

1900
01:50:50,488 --> 01:50:53,368
I remember distinctly. What the...

1901
01:50:53,408 --> 01:50:56,168
hey, what's going on around here?

1902
01:50:56,248 --> 01:51:00,928
Why, this ought to be Martini's place.

1903
